entry.title: sensors: Convert existing Generic Sensor web tests to test_driver
entry.content:
All Generic Sensor web tests are now using virtual sensors and their

implementation in WPT's testdriver.js and ChromeDriver/content_shell.

These tests no longer depend on generic_sensor_mocks.js (or Mojo mocks

in general), which has been kept only for the Device Orientation tests

at this point, and should be fully interoperable now. This also

exercises the code in //content and //services.



Compared to the JS mocks-based implementation, one of the biggest

changes is that there is no equivalent to a MockSensor that takes an

array of readings and periodically rotates and reports them to

consumers. This was an implementation detail that was kind of hard to

justify in spec terms, and the interaction between the JS timer and the

C++ code in services could lead to races between shared buffer values

and expected values (bug 1073865 is probably related, for example).



We now follow the new Automation section in the Generic Sensor spec and

explicitly require reading updates to be done via calls to

test_driver.update_virtual_sensor(). These calls might not result in a

change in readings if the sensor is not active or if the

threshold/rounding checks fail, so the tests are careful to check that a

reading has gone through when necessary. Furthermore, given how the code

in //services is implemented it is not possible to assert that a call to

update_virtual_sensor() will resolve _before_ a "reading" event is

emitted, so some Promise.all() calls are required.



The iframe tests have been essentially rewritten for clarity and to test

the right things:

* iframe_sensor_handler.html is used only by the cross-origin test. The

same-origin one simply creates the sensor in the test file directly.

* send_message_to_iframe() does not take a |reply| argument anymore.

Instead, it propagate the replies to the callers so they can do

whatever they need and we do not need to come up with values like

"success" in replies.

* The cross-origin and same-origin tests follow a workflow that is

easier to follow and mostly relies on timestamps that are part of the

public API to determine whether readings are being provided or not

depending on frame focus.



Now that the //content code is being exercised, the Ambient Light Sensor

and Magnetometer web tests need the GenericSensorExtraClasses feature to

be enabled, which is done by the newly-created

generic-sensor-extra-classes virtual test suite.



Finally, the referenceFrame test in generic-sensor-tests.js has been

disabled and a copy was added to wpt_internal, as there is no

cross-platform way to set an orientation angle and in wpt_internal it

can be set via Internals' setMockScreenOrientation().

entry.title: [Extensions] Lock extensions dev mode checking
entry.content:
Certain APIs can be restricted to users in devleoper mode. In this case,

we check the developer mode state in both the browser and the renderer.

In the browser, this always happens on the UI thread (and is thus safe);

in the renderer, though, this can happen across multiple threads (the

main thread for DOM-based contexts and worker threads for service

workers).



Add a base::Lock for access to the developer mode map to ensure map

access is safe in the renderer. This should be a no-op for the browser

(because it's only accessed on one thread, thus the lock should always

be available).

entry.title: [reland] pip-tuck: Add PipController
entry.content:
This is a reland for go/chrcl/4951313 with fixes. The issue was the

`pip_window_observation_` not being `Reset` on `OnWindowDestroying()`

which caused MSAN issues.



-



Currently there is no general controller for Picture-in-Picture (PiP)

windows. Having a dedicated controller for PiP windows would be useful

because:



1. There are multiple parts of the code that can be simplified by

introducing a controller that exists even when the PiP window does

not exist, without having to rely on `WindowState` which should be

reserved for more generic window functions. Examples include existing

`CompleteDrag()` animations and tucking behavior for PiP which we are

planning to implement.



2. A dedicated controller would allow for consolidation of the PiP

window management controls code.



This commit introduces the new class `PipController`, and also

transplants `UpdatePipBounds()` from `WindowState` to the new

`PipController`.



This new `PipController` holds a reference to the window it is managing

which can be obtained with `pip_window()`, and it is set with

`SetPipWindow()` and unset with `UnsetPipWindow()`. It also holds an

observer that observes this window when it is set.



Bug: b/305611254

entry.title: Avoid crashes when calling computedName or computedRole from DevTools
entry.content:
The crash involves re-entrance to the rendering lifecycle.



The lifecycle is supposed to be at pre-paint clean when these methods are called from devtools. However, the methods can also be called from

the (not-shipped) AOM JS APIs. The code that checked for the lifecycle

state in those methods was a hack to avoid re-entrant lifecycles. CL

4976744 revealed a situation when the lifecycle was not up-to-date

(still don't know how); in those situations, return an empty string

to avoid crashing.



This CL also migrates DevTools to use a method that is guaranteed not

to re-enter the lifecycle, which is a best practice for such situations.

entry.title: Adjust animation cancel during bookmark recycle.
entry.content:
Previously rows in the RecyclerView were not being recycled. This was

because transient state from the fade in animations was preventing View

recycling. An attempt to fix this overrode #onFailedToRecycleView and

canceled in progress animations.



However, this often didn't work correctly. #onFailedToRecycleView is

being called, sometimes, right after the binding of new data. This would

cause the new fade to not run, and leave the start drawable invisible.



To fix this, no-op #onFailedToRecycleView and return true to tell the

RecycleView to recycle the View anyway. We now cancel animations in

#onViewRecycled as a best effort.

entry.title: [webauthn] Add screen reader mode
entry.content:
The WebAuthn dialog consists of a number of sheets that the user can

navigate by interacting with their authenticator. Some of these sheets

have controls the user is expected to interact with (like a passkey

selector), and some only have less frequently used buttons (such as the

QR code sheet, where the user is expected to scan a QR code to continue,

and the only button may be "Cancel"). For those sheets, Chrome

automatically focuses one of those buttons since they are the only

actionable control. This is a problem for screen readers: they will read

the contents of the newly focused button (e.g. "Cancel"), and not the

context that has changed (e.g. "Scan this QR code" or "The request timed

out").



This CL introduces a "screen reader mode" that changes the behaviour for

sheets that do not have controls in them if a screen reader is detected.

Instead of focusing the "Cancel" or "Back" buttons, Chrome will focus

the title of the dialog. This has two benefits: it moves the screen

reader focus to the center of attention (e.g. "Scan this QR code"), and

it makes the screen reader announce that something changed (e.g.

announcing "The request timed out").



For sheets that have controls, nothing is changed. If the user just

tapped a button that says "Use another device" and then they hear "Pixel

7a, button" that should be enough context.



See

https://docs.google.com/document/d/1MSkjo9xoc0VgWypihWcH15aiyHMiHFaB8dxaiX2iJyA/



This feature is guarded by a disabled-by-default flag.

entry.title: topics: Fix Model Update Race Condition
entry.content:
When a model update comes in, it will trigger any pending calculator

requests to start. This will happen during the execution of

`AnnotatorImpl::OnModelUpdated` in between `is_valid_model_` being set

to false and later to true.



Note that if the annotations request finishes in the same stack

(e.g.: all use the override list) then this race condition will always

happen.



To resolve this, the added check of `is_valid_model_` is removed. This

check is redundant anyways since the calculator also checks whether the

incoming taxonomy version is supported, and whether `GetModelInfo()`

returns a non-null value has it's source of truth further down in the

OptGuide model execution code, which is doing the correct thing.



Furthermore, the AnnotatorImpl class takes over the model available

callbacks to check for the correct taxonomy version.



Adds a regression test

entry.title: Add invoketarget logic for popovers in button DefaultEventHandler
entry.content:
This adds logic on how buttons with an invoketarget pointing to an

element with `popover` should behave, based on the Invokers proposal.



See explainer section here:

https://open-ui.org/components/invokers.explainer/#defaults.



See related spec PR here: https://github.com/whatwg/html/pull/9875



This introduces new behavior just within the HTML Form Control

`DefaultEventHandler` function such that:



- If an `invoketarget` points to an element with `popover`

- If the `invokeaction` is `auto` or `togglePopover`, try to toggle

the popover

- If the `invokeaction` is `hidePopover`, try to hide the popover

- If the `invokeaction` is `showPopover`, try to show the popover



If the `invokeaction` is none of the above, then it will fall through

the to `HandleInvokeInternal` which is passed the lowercased atom so

element subclasses can handle their individual behaviors.

entry.content:

the duration of the animation that transitions from night light on to

off or vice versa is dictated by the reason for the change. For

example, if the user just selected new night light times in settings,

the animation is short. However, if the transition is due to a scheduled

change (ex: sunrise or sunset), the animation is long.



This introduces that concept to ScheduledFeature and most importantly,

passes the reason to ScheduledFeature::RefreshFeatureState() so that

night light (or future features) can use that reason to pick the

appropriate animation duration.

entry.title: [extensions] Convert Extension Messaging APIs over to mojo
entry.content:

between the renderer and the browser. When the

will be used.

- The mojo messages are directly dispatched to the ServiceWorker

thread avoiding the additional thread hop that the legacy IPC has.

entry.title: Add parsing support for mask-mode property
entry.content:
Implement various functions to support the parsing of values for the

newly added mask-mode property. Those values include alpha, luminance

and match-source.



Follow up patches will include support of conversion from specified

style to computed style and usage of the computed value.



Grammar:

#

= alpha | luminance | match-source

Spec: https://drafts.fxtf.org/css-masking/#the-mask-mode

entry.title: Only enable ResourceAttribution during experiment
entry.content:
ResourceAttribution is currently only used in production when the

ResourceAttributionCPUMonitor experiment is enabled, so its support

classes shouldn't be added to the PerformanceManager graph by default.



In M119 this works around a crash in ResourceContextRegistryStorage, by

making sure it's only instantiated when the experiment is running.

ResourceContextRegistryStorage was deleted in M120 so this is only an

optimization after that.
